hands_on_practices.problem:
A diploid eukaryotic organism is studied for two traits, which are controlled by genes C and D, respectively. The organism has the genotype $CcDd$. It is known that these two genes are located on two different pairs of homologous chromosomes (i.e., they are unlinked). Consider a single primary meiocyte from this organism as it undergoes meiosis. During anaphase I, homologous chromosomes are pulled apart and migrate to opposite poles of the cell. Which of the following sets represents a possible combination of alleles present in the entire collection of chromatids that moves towards one single pole of the cell during anaphase I?

A. {C, c, D, D}

B. {C, C, D, d}

C. {C, c, D, d}

D. {C, d, d, d}

E. {c, c, D, D}
